               <p>JOSEPH SMITH. I am a <rs id="t18300415-257-viclabel1429" type="occupation">solicitor</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-257-victim2237 t18300415-257-viclabel1429"></join>. On Sunday, the 21st of March, about eleven o'clock in the morning, I was in <placeName id="t18300415-257-crimeloc1430">Featherstone-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-257-crimeloc1430" type="placeName" value="Featherstone-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18300415-257-crimeloc1430" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18300415-257-off1427 t18300415-257-crimeloc1430"></join>; the prisoner took the handkerchief from my pocket - I turned round, and saw it in his hand; he flung it at me and ran; I pursued, and took him about one hundred and fifty yards off.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. How do you know this handkerchief? A. I think my initials are on it; here is a little hole in it - I did not feel any body at my pocket; I had my pocket-book in the same pocket.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. There were three boys behind me; there were no others there.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received a good character.</p>
               <p>GUILTY. Aged 16.</p>
